There's one Survivorman episode where Les Stroud goes to Papua New Guinea and ends up with diarrhea in the jungle super fucked up then proceeds to take a bunch of native drugs and get high on camera in spite of it chewing leaves and throwing up, actual 100% kino, such a wild guy.

He doesn't even say "don't do this at home" or "never take any substance that can harm your health" he just randomly gets blasted on TV with hardcore Papuan drugs until his face goes numb with zero moralizing, you can tell he had a lot of control over his show

The moment I realized how truly great Les Stroud was was when in one ep. he was starving hungry and found a nest full of small baby birds and said "nah, I can't do this" then saw the mother bird watching him from a nearby tree and said he could never eat her kids in front of her.

It's not just a Darwinian survival show like those documentaries where a penguin falls behind and they just watch it die there and say oh this is how nature is. There is morality, higher principles at work. Adam on his land, roaming creation, cultivating it... Radagast the brown.
I was actually thinking about the "don't boil a young goat in his mother's milk" commandment, very interesting. Is there direct scriptural basis or is it other tradition?
